{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530862"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:10:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:10:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14568"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14568"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.1,0.14,0.03,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103357"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7261"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2038"},{"type":"tags","id":"4185"},{"type":"tags","id":"4675"},{"type":"tags","id":"4679"},{"type":"tags","id":"4725"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11153"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36649"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103357"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about vulval pain and the appearance of her vulva. She denies any urinary symptoms or abnormal vaginal discharge. She denies having sexual intercourse though reports that she has not been able to orgasm with digital stimulation. She moved to Australia from Somalia two years ago. She recalls undergoing a surgical procedure to her genitals as a child. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never been pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. With consent, genital examination reveals narrowing of the vaginal opening with fused labia minora partially covering the introitus. There is extensive scarring across the vulva and clitoral region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate referral for defibulation","Topical oestrogen cream","Gradual vaginal dilator therapy","Pelvic floor physiotherapy","Referral for sexual counselling"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with Type III female genital mutilation/cutting (FGM/C), characterised by narrowing of the vaginal opening through creation of a covering seal. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for sexual counselling\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step, as FGM/C can have profound psychological impacts that need to be addressed alongside physical complications. A trauma-informed, culturally sensitive approach is essential. Counselling may help reduce her symptoms as well as allow the opportunity for education and understanding of her condition prior to considering further definitive management. Additionally, non-surgical strategies to reduce pain include using water-soluble lubricants during sexual intercourse, topical local anaesthetic application as required and avoiding activities that put pressure on the vulvar area (for example bicycle riding).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for defibulation\u003C/strong\u003E (surgical opening of the sealed vaginal opening) may eventually be recommended but should not be the first step. The decision to proceed with surgery should be made after appropriate counselling and when the patient feels ready. Defibulation is typically recommended for patients with Type III FGM/C who are experiencing significant symptoms or planning pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical oestrogen cream\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying anatomical and psychological issues related to FGM/C. It is useful for vaginal dryness in perimenopausal or postmenopausal women but would not be appropriate in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic floor physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be beneficial as part of a comprehensive treatment plan if there is evidence of pelvic floor dysfunction, but would not be the most appropriate first step in this scenario given the complex psychological and cultural aspects that need to be addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual vaginal dilator therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate. While dilator therapy can be useful for vaginismus or radiation-induced stenosis, it may exacerbate pain in this case and is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers should be aware that FGM/C is a form of gender-based violence and child abuse. Some patients report having FGM/C performed by health professionals in their home countries, which may cause scepticism about further medical interventions. A multidisciplinary approach involving psychological support, sexual health services, and culturally appropriate care is essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Female genital mutilation/cutting can cause significant physical and psychological complications including sexual dysfunction and dyspareunia.","Psychological support and counselling are essential first-line interventions for women with FGM/C experiencing sexual difficulties but surgical management may be required.","Defibulation should be offered to patients with Type III FGM/C experiencing complications or planning pregnancy."],"references":["WHO Guidelines on the Management of Health Complications from Female Genital Mutilation. Geneva: World Health Organization; 2016. 3, Guidance. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK368491/","Nour NM, Michels KB, Bryant AE. Defibulation to treat female genital cutting: effect on symptoms and sexual function. Obstet Gynecol. 2006 Jul;108(1):55-60. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16816056/","Isaacs D, Tobin B. Female genital mutilation and the role of health-care practitioners.  J Paid Child Health 2017; 53:523-24."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14568"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T17:39:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T17:39:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7261"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103357"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"u